If you dont already have R, you will need to install R and then R Studio (see how-to tutorial here: https://www.datacamp.com/community/tutorials/installing-R-windows-mac-ubuntu). Then copy and paste the chunks of code given below into a new R file to follow along with the analysis pipeline.

Import data

The first thing you need to do is download the data from the google spreadsheet (https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1ebwxTTXqGgh05ouvSjtzhma46DPML1hyf994NS6zjxU/edit?usp=sharing) as a .csv file:

We will then use read.csv() to read in our data, stored in a comma-separated value (.csv) file called New Larvae Growth - raw data.csv. Note that I have placed the data in a directory called C:/Users/mcros/Desktop/BuffaloWorm/data/. You will need to modify this path to reflect where you have stored that data on your computer so that R knows where to grab the data from.

dat = read.csv('C:/Users/mcros/Desktop/BuffaloWorm/data/New Larvae Growth - raw data.csv',header=T)

It is good practice to peak at data once you have imported it. There are two ways we can do that. One uses str(), short for structure, which gives us a summary of the number of variables (columns) and observations (rows) in our data frame. It also tells us what each element is. chr = character (or string of text); int = integer; num = numeric (non-integer numbers).

Plot some variables

Okay, now we need to set up our data for plotting. Lets first plot the change in mass of various components of the experiment over time. To set up our x-axis (time), we need to make sure the R knows that the Date column is populated with actual dates (not just character strings).

dat$Date2 = as.Date(dat$Date,format='%m/%d/%Y')

Uh-oh. It looks like R didnt like that our year was just two digits (21), so lets fix that and try converting to date format again.

dat$Date = apply(array(dat$Date),1,function(x){
  y=strsplit(x,'/')[[1]];
  year = paste('20',y[3],sep='');
  return(paste(y[1],y[2],year,sep='/'))
})
dat$Date2 = as.Date(dat$Date,format='%m/%d/%Y')
str(dat) #that worked!

Next lets start by plotting each petri dishs mass over time.

# First, we'll make a unique identifier for each dish by combining the colony name with the dish ID
dat$id = paste(dat$Colony,dat$Dish_ID,sep='_')
ids = unique(dat$id) #vector of unique dishes

#Let's set the color scheme for the lines in our plots. We will draw from an R package called `viridis`.
require('viridis')
## Loading required package: viridis
## Loading required package: viridisLite
pal = viridis(length(ids)) #we draw a color for each unique dish from the viridis color palette

# We will also specify a unique line type for each colony
colonies = unique(dat$Colony)
ltys = c(1,2) #solid line for Bill Dagsboro, dashed line for Daisy

# Then we'll start a new plot using the maximum and minimum dish mass to define our y-axis limits
# We'll also define a vector of dates to serve as our x-axis.
# We set col to 'white' because we are just creating an empty plot to start with.
dates = sort(unique(dat$Date2))

# Plot setup
par(oma=c(0,0,0,0),mar=c(5,5,3,1),cex.main=2,cex.lab=2,cex.axis=1.5) #specify plot margins. Order is bottom,left,top,right. Also specify text font sizes.

# Draw empty plot
plot(x=c(min(dates),max(dates)),y=c(min(dat$Dish_mass_g),max(dat$Dish_mass_g)),col='white',xlab='Date',ylab='Mass (g)',main='Petri dishes')
legend('topleft',legend=colonies,lty=ltys,bty='n') #define plot legend distinguishing colony line types

# Next, we add a line for each petri dish. We will use a `for()` loop to iterate through each dish, specifying the mass over time and a unique color to distinguish dishes and line style to distinguish colonies.
for (i in 1:length(ids)){ #for i in 1 through the number of petri dish IDs, do:
  pos = which(dat$id==ids[i]) #row position for the petri dish with id = ids[i]
  dat2 = dat[pos,] #subset dat to only contain records for ids[i]
  dat2 = dat2[order(dat2$Date2,decreasing=F),] #ensure that dates are in increasing order
  lty1 = ltys[match(unique(dat2$Colony),colonies)] #get line style correpsonding to colony of the ids[i] dish
  lines(x=dat2$Date2,y=dat2$Dish_mass_g,col=pal[i],lty=lty1,lwd=3) #draw a line
}

Question: How does this plot differ from the one above that reported larval mass over time?

Plotting everything at once

Okay, so we might be interested in plotting everything together so we can get one synoptic look at the results from the experiment. For that we will define a plotting function, and apply it to each variable of interest.

plot.exp = function(d,v){
  d$id = paste(d$Colony,d$Dish_ID,sep='_')
  ids = unique(d$id)
  pal = viridis(length(ids))
  colonies = unique(d$Colony)
  ltys = c(1,2) #this will need to be modified if more than one colony is represented
  dates = sort(unique(d$Date2))
  vpos = which(colnames(d)==v)
  plot(x=c(min(dates),max(dates)),y=c(min(d[,vpos]),max(d[,vpos])),col='white',xlab='Date',ylab='Mass (g)',main=v)
  legend('topleft',legend=colonies,lty=ltys,bty='n') 
  for (i in 1:length(ids)){
    pos = which(d$id==ids[i])
    d2 = dat[pos,]
    d2 = d2[order(d2$Date2,decreasing=F),]
    lty1 = ltys[match(unique(d2$Colony),colonies)]
    lines(x=d2$Date2,y=d2[,vpos],col=pal[i],lty=lty1,lwd=3) #draw a line
  }
}

Now that we defined our function, we can apply it to the variables of interest and make the plots

# Plot setup. Note mfrow=c(2,3). This means the plot layout includes 2 rows and 3 columns.
require('viridis')
par(mfrow=c(2,3),oma=c(0,0,0,0),mar=c(5,5,3,1),cex.main=2,cex.lab=2,cex.axis=1.5)
vars = c('Dish_mass_g','Food_mass_g','Apple_g','N_larvae','larvae_g','Avg.larva.mass')
for (i in 1:length(vars)){
  plot.exp(dat,vars[i])
}
